Probability distributions¶

2.1 Discrete distributions

2.2 Continuous distributions

2.3 Multivariate distributions (bivariate distributions)

A random variable is a value determined by chance (informal definition).
We usually use a capital letter to denote a random variable.

Example:
Let $X$ be the result of rolling a fair (balanced) die once.

Then $X$ may take the values $1, 2, 3, 4, 5,$ or $6$ by chance.

How Do We Describe a Random Variable Mathematically?¶

A probability distribution tells us the possible values of a random variable and the corresponding probabilities of those values.

For the die example, $$ P(X = k) = \frac{1}{6}, \quad k = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6. $$

Types of Random Variables¶

Discrete Random Variables¶

The possible values can be listed or counted.
The probability distribution of a discrete random variable is called a Probability Mass Function (PMF).

$$ P(x) = P(X = x) = p_x, $$

where $x$ is one of a list of specific values.

Continuous Random Variables¶

Any value within a given range can be a possible value.

Example:
The speed of a train any value between 0 and 100 miles per hour.

Mean (Expected Value)¶

The mean, or expected value, of a discrete random variable $X$ is $$ E[X] = \sum_x x p_x, $$ where $p_x$ is the probability that $X$ takes the value $x$.

The expected value is a weighted average of all possible values.

Example¶

Suppose an individual plays a gambling game with the following outcomes and probabilities:

Outcome ($) -2.00 0.00 20.00 100.00
Probability 0.75 0.15 0.049 0.001

Find the expected value of the distribution.

$$ \begin{aligned} E[X] &= (-2)(0.75) + (0)(0.15) + (20)(0.049) + (100)(0.001) \\ &= -1.5 + 0 + 0.98 + 0.10 \\ &= -0.42. \end{aligned} $$

This means that, in the long run, the average loss per game is $0.42.

Variance of a Discrete Random Variable¶

The variance of a discrete random variable is given by $$ \operatorname{Var}(X) = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2. $$

2.1.1 Special Discrete Random Variables¶

A. Bernoulli Distribution¶

A random variable $X$ is said to have a Bernoulli distribution with parameter $p$ if $$ X \sim \mathrm{Bernoulli}(p), \quad 0 \le p \le 1. $$

  • Support: $x \in \{0, 1\}$
  • Probability Mass Function (PMF):
$$ P(X = x) = p^x (1 - p)^{1 - x}, \quad x \in \{0, 1\}. $$

Example:
Toss a coin once, where the probability of obtaining a head (success) is $p$.

B. Binomial Distribution¶

A random variable $X$ is said to have a Binomial distribution with parameters $n$ and $p$ if $$ X \sim \mathrm{Binomial}(n, p), \quad n \in \mathbb{N}, \; 0 \le p \le 1. $$

  • Support: $x = 0, 1, \dots, n$
  • Probability Mass Function (PMF):
$$ P(X = x) = \binom{n}{x} p^x (1 - p)^{n - x}, \quad x = 0, 1, \dots, n. $$

A binomial random variable models the number of successes in a fixed number of independent and identical trials, where each trial has the same probability of success.

Example:

Let $X$ be the number of heads obtained when tossing a fair coin 9 times.

Then $X$ has a binomial distribution with

  • $n = 9$ (the number of trials), and
  • $p = 0.5$ (the probability of success in each trial).

C. Poisson Distribution¶

A random variable $X$ is said to have a Poisson distribution with parameter $\lambda$ if $$ X \sim \mathrm{Poisson}(\lambda), \quad \lambda > 0. $$

  • Support: $x = 0, 1, 2, \dots$
  • Probability Mass Function (PMF):
$$ P(X = x) = e^{-\lambda} \frac{\lambda^x}{x!}, \quad x = 0, 1, 2, \dots $$

A Poisson random variable models the number of occurrences of an event in a fixed amount of time, space, or distance, assuming that the event occurs at a constant average rate $\lambda$ and that occurrences are independent.

Examples:

  1. The number of phone calls received in one hour ($0, 1, 2, \dots$).
  2. The number of hurricanes in Texas next year.
  3. The number of DNA mutations in a segment of DNA.

Parameter $\lambda$: the rate of occurences.

Probability calculation for these special distributions¶

Negative Binomial Distribution¶

A negative binomial distribution is to model the number of failures procede (until) the $r$-th success.

A negative binomial distribution has two parameters: $r$ (the required number of successes) , p = Probability of a success

Counting the number of trials (successes + failures) required to achieve a specified number of successes.

the number of trials = the number of failures + r

A success = a type of the results

A failure = all other types of the results

The mean of a negative binomial is

$EX = r/p - r = r(1-1/p) = r (1-p)/p$

$Var(X) = ... $

Flipping a coin: a success = a head, a failure = a tail

Check if a component is defective or not: a success = A defective item , a failure = a non-defective item.

Example: In a clinical trial, a treatment has a 30% probability of success for each patient. Let $X$ be the number of patients treated until 5 successful responses are observed. $$ X \sim \text{Negative Binomial}(r = 5, p = 0.3) + 5 $$

Example: A student is selling candy door to door to raise money for a school fundraiser. Each household independently agrees to buy candy with probability 0.2. The student wants to sell candy to 5 households.
What is the distribution of the number of house where he does not make a sell until he sell candy to 5 household?

       A success = A house with a sell

       r = 5

       p = probability of a success in one trial = 0.2 

       Negative binomial with r = 5,  p = 0.2

In average, how many houses does the kid need to visit until he sell 5?

    Expecte number of trials =   r/p = 5/0.2 = 25

Intutively, a negative binomial is related to model the effort needed to acheive a goal (r-th success).

Many biological count data exhibit overdispersion, where the variance exceeds the mean, violating the Poisson assumption.

The mean, the variance

Examples:

  • Number of parasites per host

  • RNA-seq gene expression read counts

  • Number of insects per plant

  • Disease case counts across regions

Choosing the correct discrete distribution depends on what is fixed and what is being counted.¶

Use the Poisson distribution when:

  • An average rate (mean) of events per unit (time, page, distance, area, etc.) is given, and
  • You are asked to find the probability of observing $n$ events in a fixed interval.

Typical wording includes phrases such as on average, rate per unit, or expected number of events.

Example:

  • The number of typos per 100 pages
  • The number of phone calls in two hours
  • The number of accidents per mile

Use the Binomial distribution when:

  • There is a fixed number of trials $n$, and
  • Each trial can be grouped into only two outcomes (success/failure), with
  • A known (or implied) probability of success $p$, and
  • You are asked for the probability of $k$ successes out of $n$ trials.

Typical wording includes phrases such as out of, exactly $k$, or fixed number of trials.

Example:

  • Number of defective items in a sample of $n$ products
  • Number of heads in tossing a coin $n$ times

Use the Negative Binomial distribution when:

  • The probability of success $p$ is fixed, and
  • Trials continue until (precede, before) a specified number of successes $r$ is reached, and
  • You are asked about the number of failures before the $r$th success (or equivalently, the total number of trials until $r$ successes).

Typical wording includes phrases such as until, before, or how many trials are needed.

Example:

  • Number of customers who do not buy before the $5$th sale
  • Number of non-defective items inspected before finding $r$ defective ones

2.2 Continuous distributions¶

To model the driving speed of a randomly selected car in the highway, we may use a density curve: in mathematics, we call it "probablity density function " (pdf)

Let $X$ be a continuous random variable with probability density function $f(x)$.

Probability¶

$$ P(a \le X \le b) = \int_a^b f(x)\,dx $$

Expected Value (the mean)¶

$$ \mathbb{E}[X] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x f(x)\,dx $$

Variance¶

$$ \mathrm{Var}(X) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} (x - \mathbb{E}[X])^2 f(x)\,dx $$

or $$ \mathrm{Var}(X) = \mathbb{E}[X^2] - (\mathbb{E}[X])^2 $$

2.2.1 Normal distributions¶

History: The Normal distribution was first introduced by Abraham de Moivre in 1733 to approximate binomial probabilities. Later, Carl Friedrich Gauss (hence "Gaussian") popularized it in the early 19th century for analyzing astronomical and measurement errors. Its importance comes from the Central Limit Theorem, which states that sums of many independent random variables tend to follow a Normal distribution, regardless of the original distributions.

Normal (Gaussian) Distribution $N(\mu,\sigma^2)$ has a Probability Density Function as $$ f(x) = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}} \exp\left(-\dfrac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}\right) $$

where

  • $\mu$: mean (location / center of the distribution)
  • $\sigma$: standard deviation (spread)
  • $\sigma^2$: variance

A normal distribution is bell curved, symetrical, the mean is at $\mu$ and the variance is $\sigma^2$

Why normal distributions are important?

1). Many natural occuring characteristics such as "ph value" of the rain, "height" of all 15 years old males, weights of ... have bell curved patterns if we construct a histogram for the data. A theorical model (normal distributions) happens to describe these patterns very well.

2). Central limit theorm, in the therotical aspects.

A standard normal distribuiton: a normal distribution with the mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.
$$Z \sim N(0, 1^2) $$

2.2.2 Exponential distributions¶

Probability Density Function $$ f(x) = \begin{cases} \lambda e^{-\lambda x}, & x \ge 0 \\ 0, & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} $$

Parameters:

  • $\lambda$: rate parameter (the same meaning of the parameter in Poisson distributions)
    • Average number of events per unit time
    • Larger $\lambda$ implies shorter expected waiting time
$$ \mathbb{E}[X] = \dfrac{1}{\lambda} $$$$ \mathrm{Var}(X) = \dfrac{1}{\lambda^2} $$
Applications¶
  • Time before the next occurence, time between two occurences
  • Queueing systems
  • Memoryless processes

Example: suppose the service rate is 0.1 customers per minute in a window of the post office. What is the distribution of the waiting time of the next customer?

$X~exp(0.1)$.

EX = 10

The Exponential distribution is a special case of the Gamma distribution with shape parameter = 1. It is defined only for positive values and is widely used to model time until an event occurs, with a single rate parameter > 0 (or scale = 1/), which determines the expected time between events.

  • Reliability Engineering: Models the time until failure of a component when failures occur at a constant rate. The rate represents the average frequency of failures, helping engineers estimate product lifetimes and maintenance schedules.

  • Queuing Theory: Models waiting times between arrivals or services, such as customer arrivals at a bank or calls at a call center. Here, is the average arrival or service rate, allowing prediction of queue lengths and service efficiency.

  • Meteorology: Used to model time between rainfall events. The rate represents the expected frequency of rainfall occurrences.

  • Finance & Insurance: Models time between claims or financial losses. reflects the expected frequency of such events, helping actuaries in risk assessment and premium calculation.

  • Survival Analysis / Healthcare: Models the time until an event such as equipment failure or patient relapse. The rate corresponds to the hazard rate, representing the instantaneous probability of the event occurring at any given time.

Example: suppose the service rate is 0.1 customers per minute in a window of the post office. Find the probability the waiting time is more than 5 minutes.

$X~exp(0.1)$.

2.2.3 Gamma Distribution $\Gamma(\alpha,\beta)$¶

(Shape $\alpha$, Rate $\beta$) - Textbook

Probability Density Function¶

$$ f(x) = \begin{cases} \dfrac{\beta^\alpha}{\Gamma(\alpha)} x^{\alpha-1} e^{-\beta x}, & x \ge 0 \\ 0, & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} $$

Parameters Interpretation¶

  • $\alpha$: shape parameter
    • Controls skewness
    • Often interpreted as the number of events
  • $\beta$: rate parameter
    • Controls decay speed

Mean¶

$$ \mathbb{E}[X] = \dfrac{\alpha}{\beta} $$

Variance¶

$$ \mathrm{Var}(X) = \dfrac{\alpha}{\beta^2} $$

Applications¶

  • Total waiting time for multiple events
  • Reliability analysis
  • Bayesian inference

Because it is flexible and defined only for positive values, the Gamma distribution is widely used in various fields. Its two parametersthe shape parameter > 0 and the rate parameter > 0 (or scale = 1/)allow it to model a wide range of behaviors, from highly skewed to nearly symmetric distributions:

  • Reliability Engineering: Models the time-to-failure of mechanical or electronic components. Here, can represent the number of cumulative stress events leading to failure, and controls the rate at which failure occurs, helping engineers predict product lifetimes.

  • Meteorology: Frequently used to model rainfall amounts. Since rainfall is non-negative and typically right-skewed, the Gamma distribution fits well. The shape reflects how concentrated rainfall is around typical amounts, while the rate scales the intensity, capturing rare but extreme rainfall events.

  • Finance & Insurance: Actuaries use it to model the size of insurance claims or financial losses. The shape parameter represents the frequency of claims contributing to total loss, and the rate determines the typical size of individual claims, effectively modeling long-tail risks for premium pricing.

  • Queuing Theory: Models waiting times for service, such as how long a customer waits in line or a call center agent takes to resolve an issue. Here, can represent the number of sequential service stages or tasks, and governs the average time per stage, allowing flexible modeling of total waiting times.

  • Bayesian Statistics: Commonly used as a conjugate prior for the rate parameter in Poisson or Exponential models. The shape reflects prior knowledge

Example: suppose the service rate is 0.1 customers per minute in a window of the post office. What is the distribution of the waiting time of if two customers is in front of you?

Waitig time for 3 customers (Waiting time to have the third occurences):

$\Gamma(\alpha = 3,\beta = 0.1)$

2.2.4 Weibull Distributions¶

The Weibull distribution is a flexible probability distribution used to model lifetimes, failure times, and extreme events. It is defined only for positive values. Its key parameters are:

  • Shape parameter $k > 0$ (sometimes denoted as $\beta$): Controls the failure rate behavior.

    • $k < 1$: Decreasing failure rate (early failures dominate)
    • $k = 1$: Constant failure rate (reduces to the Exponential distribution)
    • $k > 1$: Increasing failure rate (wear-out failures dominate)

  • Scale parameter $\lambda > 0$ (sometimes denoted as $\alpha$): Stretches or compresses the distribution along the x-axis; it represents the characteristic life.

For $x \ge 0$:

$$ f(x; k, \lambda) = \frac{k}{\lambda} \left(\frac{x}{\lambda}\right)^{k-1} e^{-(x/\lambda)^k} $$

Cumulative Distribution Function (CDF)

$$ F(x; k, \lambda) = 1 - e^{-(x/\lambda)^k}, \quad x \ge 0 $$

Mean and Variance

The Weibull distribution is a flexible probability distribution widely used to model lifetimes, failure times, and extreme events. It is defined for positive values and has two key parameters:

  • Shape parameter k > 0: Determines the failure rate behavior.
    • k < 1: Decreasing failure rate (early failures dominate).
    • k = 1: Constant failure rate (equivalent to Exponential).
    • k > 1: Increasing failure rate (wear-out failures dominate).
  • Scale parameter > 0: Stretches or compresses the distribution along the x-axis, controlling the characteristic life.

History¶

The Weibull distribution was introduced by Waloddi Weibull in 1951 to model material strength and reliability. Its flexibility in modeling different failure rates makes it extremely useful in engineering, reliability analysis, and survival studies.

Applications¶

  • Reliability Engineering / Survival Analysis: Models time-to-failure of components, machinery, or devices.

    • k describes how the failure rate changes over time.
    • represents the characteristic lifetime where about 63.2% of items have failed.

  • Meteorology & Environmental Science: Models wind speeds, rainfall extremes, or other natural phenomena.

    • k controls the shape of the distribution of extreme events.
    • sets the scale of typical extreme values.

  • Finance & Risk Management: Models extreme losses or insurance claim sizes.

    • k adjusts the tail heaviness, capturing the probability of very rare but large losses.
    • scales the magnitude of typical losses.

  • Material Science: Models breaking strength of materials under stress.

    • k indicates the variability in material strength.
    • gives the characteristic strength threshold.

  • Queueing & Industrial Systems: Models time until an event in systems w

# Support for the fitted model
y = 0:n
pmf = dbinom(y, size = n,  prob = p)             #the probability mass function

# Plot histogram (normalized) and fitted PMF
hist(
  x,
  breaks = seq(-0.5, max(x) + 0.5, by = 1),
  probability = TRUE,
  xlab = "Value",
  ylab = "Probability",
  main = "Histogram and Fitted Binomial Model"
)

#The fitted model
lines(y, pmf, type = "b", pch = 16)
